# Backend — C++ Services

## Status

The developer is actively learning C++, with prior Node.js BE experience. AI should guide and explain, not write code for them.

## Services (3 total)

| Service | Port | Single responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| `core-api` | 8080 | Auth, users, video metadata, search, favorites |
| `uploader-api` | 8081 | File ingestion + transcoding trigger only |
| `watcher-api` | 8082 | HLS manifest and segment serving only |

See `docs/adr/011-service-architecture.md` for the full boundary rationale.

## Framework

**Drogon** — chosen for maximum async throughput and native HTTP/2. See `docs/adr/001-cpp-framework.md`.

- Use coroutine-based handlers (`co_await`) for all I/O operations
- Never block the event loop with synchronous calls (file I/O, DB queries, FFmpeg)
- Drogon's built-in PostgreSQL and Redis clients must be used (they are async-native)

## Build System

- **CMake + Ninja** — see `docs/adr/012-build-system.md`
- CMake generates the build graph; Ninja executes it with automatic parallelism (uses all cores)
- Build artifacts go to `build/` (gitignored)
- Debug and Release configs must both be defined in `CMakeLists.txt`

```bash
# Commands you run yourself (do not ask AI to run these)
cmake -S . -B build -G Ninja -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug
ninja -C build
```

## Code Structure (per service)

```
services/{service-name}/
├── src/
│   ├── main.cpp            ← entry point only — registers controllers, starts server
│   ├── controllers/        ← Drogon HttpController subclasses (one per route group)
│   ├── core/               ← business logic (transcoding, file serving, auth logic)
│   ├── middleware/         ← JWT validation filter, rate limiting
│   └── utils/              ← helpers, error types, logging
├── include/                ← public headers
├── tests/                  ← Google Test (gtest + gmock) — see ADR 015
└── CMakeLists.txt
```

Apply this structure to all three services: `core-api`, `uploader-api`, `watcher-api`.

## Conventions

- Headers use `#pragma once` (not include guards)
- No raw `new`/`delete` — use smart pointers (`std::unique_ptr`, `std::shared_ptr`)
- Prefer `std::string_view` over `const std::string&` for read-only string params
- All config (ports, DB URLs, file paths, JWT secret) loaded from environment variables — never hardcoded
- [FILL: logging — spdlog recommended for async-safe structured logging]

## Auth (JWT Validation)

- All three C++ services validate the JWT access token on every protected route
- JWT validation is a Drogon filter (middleware) — applied per route group
- Token payload carries `role` claim: `viewer` or `uploader`
- `core-api` owns all auth endpoints: login, refresh, logout
- `uploader-api` routes require `role == "uploader"`
- `watcher-api` routes require `role == "viewer"` or `"uploader"`
- Redis refresh token logic lives in `core-api` only

## Database

- **PostgreSQL** — persistent data (users, videos, permissions, upload records)
- **Redis** — refresh tokens, video metadata cache, rate limiting
- Use Drogon's built-in async DB clients for both — do not use synchronous drivers

## FFmpeg Integration (Async, HLS output)

- **Phase 1**: FFmpeg CLI via `popen()` — see `docs/adr/004-transcoding.md`
- **Phase 2**: Migrate to libav (planned, not immediate)
- FFmpeg calls run in a dedicated thread pool — never block the Drogon event loop
- See `docs/adr/008-async-transcoding.md` for the full async strategy

Transcode flow per upload:
1. `uploader-api` saves raw file, pushes job to Redis queue, returns 202
2. Thread pool worker pops job, spawns one FFmpeg process **per resolution in parallel**
3. Each FFmpeg outputs HLS: `.ts` segments + resolution `.m3u8`
4. Worker generates `master.m3u8` after all resolutions complete
5. Updates PostgreSQL status to `ready`, triggers user notification

Example FFmpeg command shape (you write this yourself):
```
ffmpeg -i {input} -vf scale={width}:{height} -hls_time 6 -hls_playlist_type vod \
  -hls_segment_filename "{CHUNK_STORAGE_PATH}/{video_id}/{resolution}/seg_%04d.ts" \
  {CHUNK_STORAGE_PATH}/{video_id}/{resolution}/{resolution}.m3u8
```

## Streaming / Chunking (HLS)

Protocol: **HLS** — see `docs/adr/006-streaming-protocol.md`

Storage layout (root from env var `CHUNK_STORAGE_PATH`):
```
{CHUNK_STORAGE_PATH}/
└── {video_id}/
    ├── master.m3u8          ← lists all resolution playlists
    ├── 1080p/
    │   ├── 1080p.m3u8       ← segment playlist for this resolution
    │   ├── seg_0001.ts
    │   ├── seg_0002.ts
    │   └── ... (up to seg_9999.ts — ~16hrs at 6s segments)
    ├── 720p/
    ├── 480p/
    └── 360p/
```

Segment filename format: `seg_%04d.ts` (FFmpeg `-hls_segment_filename` flag) — see ADR 010.

- `watcher-api` serves `.m3u8` and `.ts` files directly from disk as static-like responses
- `hls.js` in the browser requests `master.m3u8` first, then switches resolution playlists automatically
- HTTP delivery: standard GET requests per segment — no range requests needed for HLS
